## YAML File Structure

Every YAML manifest MUST include:
1. A header comment block with `Purpose:` section explaining what the file does
2. A `Checklist for developers` section with numbered action items
3. Use `---` as document separator at the start

### Header Template

```yaml
---
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#                       Purpose:
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# [Describe what this file does and its role in the deployment]
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#           Checklist for developers using this [ResourceType]
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. [First action item - typically replacing 'template' placeholder]
# 2. [Second action item - configuration specific to resource type]
# 3. [Additional items as needed]
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

## Creating New Kubernetes Manifests

When creating new Kubernetes manifests:
1. Always start with the header comment block template above
2. Include appropriate checklist items for the resource type
3. Use consistent indentation (2 spaces)
4. Reference existing files as patterns for new resources

## Modifying Existing Manifests

When modifying existing manifests:
1. Preserve the header comment structure
2. Update checklist items if adding new configurable fields
3. Keep placeholder `template` values for reusability
